<br />
Am I missing anything? Probably not worth the purchase for only a couple of games. <br><BR><font size=1>18:30 11-22-2011</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#CCCCCC>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#CCCCCC><font class="bfont"><B>Iceman </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/magic/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Iceman '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#CCCCCC' ><font class="bfont">Arkham City, anybody playing it ? <br><BR><font size=1>10:34 11-22-2011</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>_Armaedes_ </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/magic/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=_Armaedes_ '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">I played one round of MW multiplayer, got totally trashed, and never played a CoD game again, single player or multi-player.  Because Pat&#39;s right - buying it for the SP is a rip-off, and the multiplayer takes a lot of time to get good enough at to enjoy.  Not for me.<br />
<br />
Skyrim though, is awesome.  Last night I saw a mammoth off in the distance, and I needed a mammoth hide to forge some armor, so I sneak up on it and pull out my bow.  I look all around to either side of the mammoth and see nothing else, so I feel safe and let loose with an arrow.  I immediately hear a crashing in the brush behind me.  I turn around and it&#39;s another mammoth and the giant that herds them, charging straight for me.  I put my bow away and start to run, but I only make it about 50 feet when a dragon lands right in front of me.  So I dodge out of the way and the dragon engages the giant and mammoth.  I stand back to let them take care of each other, and that&#39;s when I&#39;m hit from behind by a blast of frost - a blood dragon had landed behind me.  There was nowhere to run but back into the fray.  This was a rare Skyrim situation (2 dragons at once) made worse by also fighting two mammoths and a giant.  In the end, I took them all out but lost my follower in the process, so I wasn&#39;t able to haul all of the gear back to town.<br />
<br />
Such a cool game. <br><BR><font size=1>09:56 11-22-2011</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#CCCCCC>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#CCCCCC><font class="bfont"><B>Patrick M. S </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/magic/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Patrick M. S '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#CCCCCC' ><font class="bfont">MW3 actually fixes and addresses that problem kinda brilliantly. They sort of realized &#39;oops&#39; in the major characters they killed in MW2. It&#39;s neat. <br><BR><font size=1>23:13 11-21-2011</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Guero </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/magic/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Guero '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">The gimmick (drag mouse to see spoiler)<div style=background-color:red;color:red;foreground-color:red>of killing the character that you&#39;re playing during the story missions</div> is now kind of lame. In MW1, it was genuinely shocking (at least to me). MW2 ran that well dry. <br><BR><font size=1>19:15 11-21-2011</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#CCCCCC>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#CCCCCC><font class="bfont"><B>Patrick M. S </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/magic/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Patrick M. S '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#CCCCCC' ><font class="bfont">oh yeah, and right before that you&#39;ve been driven to be executed. That was brutal. <br />
